<font color="#FF0000">RE: PASTRY PERSON</font><br>
<tt>Sun Oct 12 16:16:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I don't know what name to call you by MTF-anymouse-Humming Eagle-Tatekohommni, Wambli. Do you have a preference ?   I give you the honor you deserve.  I have no desire to enter into a pissing battle. You win!  I have alway loved and respected the men who served their country in Vietnam and if I hadn't,  I wouldn't have put my own life on the line by going in support of them. I have no intention to fight you now, we are on the same side. Welcome me inside the parimeter.  It's cold and lonely out here.   My role in Vietnam was not to participate in the battle but to be there for men such as yourself who found their way to where I was because of that participation. You did your job.  I did mine.  <br><br>
No, I wasn't personnally involved in the killing and from that perspective I cannot claim to know how you feel especially without having shared your story.  That doesn't mean I am clueless on what those who did participate went through, or that I cannot empathize. As a caseworker, I listened and learned from the wounded  in order to help those I had contact with.  I had to try and deal with the traumas as if they were my own,  first to understand,  and then to help the person I was talking with to find their own solutions.   For those who confided in me, I kept their secrets. From that perspective you may call me Black bear woman.  I  too was a warrior, not fighting with physical weapons but fighting a battle none the less on  a different kind of battlefield.  Many of my attitutes were picked up by osmosis from the men on the wards who were predominately combat types.  I may be one of the few women in the world who can understand that men can do terrible things in war honorably.<br><br>
A combat vet that I carried on an extended on-line discussion with, told me to never  accept the title of REMF.  He said that REMF is an attitude not a location where one served. <br><br>
If I stepped on your feathers and came across as a spokesman for you, please except my apology.  If you are there to speak for yourself you most certainly should.  On the other hand, when you aren't there, don't expect me not to stand up for Vietnam vets. I hope you would do the same for the women who served as well.  <br><br>
I don't think you meant anything negative by your use of the term Pastry Person but I must ask you to please stop using it.  I had a very unpleasant experience in a veteran's chat room where I was personally attacked  by  one of the men who upon entry  into the room and finding out I had been with the Red Cross went off  about donut dollies selling sex and called them/me a pastry pig by association.   The connotations associated with pastry will never be the same for me anymore.  Donut dolly as a term of endearment is fine, but not if used as a slur or a put down.<br><br>

<p><code>--   (Classlass) </code><p>


